span class="fa fa-pinterest"></span></div> </a><a onclick="window.open('http://www.tumblr.com/share/link?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwapo.st%2F19lACsJ&name=Sounding+the+alarm&description=','','width=550,height=450,scrollbars=no');return false;" tabindex=_tbidx_> <div class="tumblr tool last mobile"><span class="hideText">Share on Tumblr</span><span class="fa fa-tumblr"></span></div> </a></div> </div> </div> <div id="slug_tiffany_tile" data-ad-type="tiffany_tile" class="left" style="display:none;padding-left:20px !important;height:auto;max-height:60px;overflow:hidden;"> <div id="wpni_adi_tiffany_tile" class="ads slug tiffany_tile header"></div> </div> <div class=" utility-tools-wrapper"> <div class="utility-tools-primary margin-top"> <div class="social-tools "> <div class="textresizer tool first mobile"><span class="hideText" tabindex=_tbidx_>Resize Text</span><span class="fa fa-font"></span></div><a onclick="window.print();" tabindex=_tbidx_> <div class="print tool mobile"><span class="hideText">Print Article</span><span class="fa fa-print"></span></div> </a><a href="#" onclick="wp_pb.report('comments', 'showComments');$('.echo_container_placeholder')[0].scrollIntoView();return false;" tabindex=_tbidx_> <div class="comments tool last mobile"><span class="hideText">Comments</span><span class="fa fa-comments"></span> <span id="echo_container" class="echo_container comment-vars echo-counter text" guid="http://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/nightmare-bacteria-are-real-and-the-us-needs-to-act-fast/2013/10/20/e457beec-3828-11e3-8a0e-4e2cf80831fc_story.html"></span></div> </a></div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="clear"></div> </div> <div class="pb-scatter"> <div id="chain-2" class="pb-layout-item pb-chain pb-two chain-2" data-pb-columns="2"> <div id="article-opinions_1401987413282_950" class=" pb-feature pb-chained pb-f-article-article-body pb-f-theme-normal" data-pb-async="false" data-pb-columns="" data-pb-name="article-article-body" data-pb-content-uri="/pb/opinions/nightmare-bacteria-are-real-and-the-us-needs-to-act-fast/2013/10/20/e457beec-3828-11e3-8a0e-4e2cf80831fc_story.html" data-pb-content-editable=""> <div id="article-body" class="article-body"> <div class="pb-sig-line hasnt-headshot has-0-headshots hasnt-bio is-not-column"> <span class="pb-byline">By David E. Hoffman</span> <span class="pb-timestamp">October 20, 2013</span> </div> <article> <div class="intro"> <p> <i>David E. Hoffman is a contributing editor to The Post.</i> </p> </div> <p>Last spring, Arjun Srinivasan, an associate director of the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, delivered a presentation to state health officials with some alarming information. Before the year 2000, he said, it was rare to find cases of bacteria resistant to carbapenems, a class of powerful, last-resort antibiotics. But by February 2013 they had been seen in almost every state. Srinivasan also briefed Thomas Frieden, director of the CDC. On March 5, Frieden issued a public warning about “nightmare” bacteria, <a href="http://www.nbcnews.com/health/more-bad-news-about-nightmare-bacteria-cdc-says-1C8701174" title="www.nbcnews.com">a family of germs known as CREs</a>. They can kill up to half the patients who get bloodstream infections from them, resist most or all antibiotics and spread resistance to other strains. </p> <p>Last month, Frieden released a <a href="http://www.cdc.gov/drugresistance/threat-report-2013/">report</a> estimating that at least 2 million Americans get infections each year that are <a href="http://www.cdc.gov/media/releases/2013/t0916_health-threats.html">resistant to antibiotics</a> and that at least 23,000 people die as a result. Margaret Chan, director general of the World Health Organization, warned last year: “<a href="http://www.who.int/dg/speeches/2012/amr_20120314/en/">A post-antibiotic era means, in effect, an end to modern medicine as we know it.</a> Things as common as strep throat or a child’s scratched knee could once again kill.” </p> <p>The words of Frieden and Chan ought to make our hair stand on end. But my reporting for the documentary “<a href="http://ec2-107-21-207-21.compute-1.amazonaws.com/wgbh/pages/frontline/hunting-the-nightmare-bacteria/">Hunting the Nightmare Bacteria</a>,” which is to air Tuesday on PBS’s “Frontline,” suggests that past warnings about antimicrobial resistance were largely discarded. This is not a threat that causes people to jump out of their chairs. It always seems to be someone else’s problem, some other time. </p> <p>We ought to snap out of our long complacency.</p><div class="inline-content inline-gallery-embedded"> <link href="//www.washingtonpost.com/pb/resources/compact/type/ssiSingle/styles/b2571cf5dfafe5a7760aba08fea63fd6.css?_=8ac93a" rel="stylesheet"/> <link href="//www.washingtonpost.com/pb/resources/compact/template/gallery-embed/styles/6bf32f216c50d6ab0c64d68d81d5ebb5.css?_=8ac93a" rel="stylesheet"/> <link href="//www.washingtonpost.com/pb/resource/style-gallery-embed-6a954a58.css?_=8ac93a" rel="stylesheet"/> <script src="//www.washingtonpost.com/pb/resource/headjs-gallery-embed-6a954a58.js?_=8ac93a" type="text/javascript"></script> <div class="pb-feature-ssi-single pb-f-gallery-gallery" data-pb-content-uri="/pb/galleryEmbed/f4165114-883c-11e2-98a3-b3db6b9ac586" data-pb-name="gallery-gallery" id="gallery-embed_1398960200458_283"> <div class="wp-volt-gal wp-volt-gal-p-end-circle wp-volt-gal-promo-stub wp-volt-gal-on-promo-slide" data-category="Outlook" data-commercial-node="opinions" data-permalink="http://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/memorable-myths-of-2013/2013/03/08/f4165114-883c-11e2-98a3-b3db6b9ac586_gallery.html" data-preroll-zone="" data-published="1359585900" data-section="opinions" data-show-interstitials="true" data-show-preroll="true" data-slug="memorable-myths-of-2013" data-subsection="" data-title="Myths of 2013" data-uuid="f4165114-883c-11e2-98a3-b3db6b9ac586"> <div class="wp-volt-gal-bar"> <div class="wp-volt-gal-nav"> <div class="wp-volt-gal-nav-number"><span class="wp-volt-gal-nav-number-current">1</span> of 52</div> <div class="wp-volt-gal-nav-buttons"> <div class="wp-volt-gal-nav-button wp-volt-gal-nav-prev"></div> <div class="wp-volt-gal-nav-button wp-volt-gal-nav-next"></div> </div> </div> <div class="wp-volt-gal-buttons"> <div class="wp-volt-gal-button wp-volt-gal-button-fullscreen">Full Screen</div> <div class="wp-volt-gal-button wp-volt-gal-button-autoplay">Autoplay</div> <div class="wp-volt-gal-bar-pie"></div> <div class="wp-volt-gal-button wp-volt-gal-button-close">Close</div> </div> </div> <div class="wp-volt-gal-main"> <div class="wp-volt-gal-photos"> <div class="wp-volt-gal-slide wp-volt-gal-photo" data-buy="false" data-caption='MYTH: Lack of access to fresh fruits and vegetables is responsible for the obesity epidemic. “The Obama administration’s Healthy Food Financing Initiative is meant to help low-income communities that lack access to fresh food,” writes Deborah Cohen in “&lt;a href="http://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/five-myths-about-obesity/2013/12/27/cd7f5b3a-69c4-11e3-8b5b-a77187b716a3_story.html"&gt;Five myths about obesity&lt;/a&gt;.” “Although the U.S Department of Agriculture estimates that fewer than 5 percent of Americans live in these ‘food deserts,’ about 65 percent of the nation’s population is overweight or obese.” Here, a meal at a Shake Shack restaurant in Moscow.' data-credit="Andrey Rudakov/Bloomberg" data-image="http://www.washingtonpost.com/rw/2010-2019/WashingtonPost/2013/12/27/Outlook/Images/117140142.jpg?env=A" data-max-width="4000" data-ratio="1.485" data-title=" " data-uuid="6cbd6612-6f27-11e3-a523-fe73f0ff6b8d"><div class="wp-volt-gal-slide-gal-title"></div></div><div class="wp-volt-gal-slide wp-volt-gal-photo" data-buy="false" data-caption='MYTH: Canada, Russia and Denmark are each attempting a North Pole land grab. “Canada’s and Russia’s efforts to determine their rights over the North Pole’s soil and subsurface are part of a well-established international process,” writes Rob Huebert in “&lt;a href="http://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/five-myths-about-the-north-pole/2013/12/20/22267a62-6694-11e3-8b5b-a77187b716a3_story.html"&gt;Five myths about the North Pole&lt;/a&gt;.” “Under the terms of the 1982 &lt;a data-xslt="_http" href="http://www.un.org/depts/los/convention_agreements/convention_overview_convention.htm"&gt;United Nations Convention on the Law of the Sea&lt;/a&gt;, both states have the right to resources such as oil, gas, minerals and anything else that exists on the bottom of the ocean more than 200 nautical miles off their coasts.” Here, Canada‘s HMCS Fredericton on maneuvers in Frobisher Bay at the southern tip of Baffin Island, Canada.' data-credit="MICHEL COMTE/AFP/Getty Images" data-image="http://www.washingtonpost.com/rw/2010-2019/WashingtonPost/2013/12/20/Outlook/Images/Was8128240.jpg?env=A" data-max-width="3072" data-ratio="1.333" data-title=" " data-uuid="56f2514a-69bd-11e3-8b5b-a77187b716a3"></div><div class="wp-volt-gal-slide wp-volt-gal-photo" data-buy="false" data-caption='MYTH: Opposition to the Common Core academic standards is coming primarily from the tea party and white suburban moms. “&lt;span&gt;Resistance to the Common Core is coming from every political direction&lt;/span&gt;,” writes Valerie Strauss in “&lt;a href="http://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/five-myths-about-the-common-core/2013/12/13/da05f832-5c40-11e3-be07-006c776266ed_story.html"&gt;Five myths about the Common Core&lt;/a&gt;.” “Glenn Beck warned his listeners: ‘You as a parent are going to be completely pushed out of the loop’.. . . On the left, Diane Ravitch, the most vocal critic of school reforms that focus on standardization, has suggested that federal promotion of the Common Core ‘may well have been illegal.’” Here, a fifth-grader in Middletown, Del., works on an English language arts lesson at a school implementing Common Core in October. ' data-credit="Steve Ruark/AP" data-image="http://www.washingtonpost.com/rw/2010-2019/WashingtonPost/2013/12/13/Outlook/Images/Common_Core_The_Classroom-03ba6.jpg?env=A" data-max-width="4110" data-ratio="1.526" data-title=" " data-uuid="0dc73ed2-6444-11e3-91b3-f2bb96304e34"></div><div class="wp-volt-gal-slide wp-volt-gal-photo" data-buy="false" data-caption='MYTH: Locals in disaster areas wait for the international community to come save them.”The first responders after any emergency are always the survivors,” Jessica Alexander writes in “&lt;a href="http://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/five-myths-about-helping-the-philippines/2013/12/05/812d6d62-52ef-11e3-9fe0-fd2ca728e67c_story.html"&gt;Five myths about helping the Philippines&lt;/a&gt;.” “Before Typhoon Haiyan struck, a large international aid organization on the ground in the Philippines employed 95 local staffers. Within a week after the storm, it had hired close to 3,000 Filipinos.” Here, children play among debris of destroyed houses in Tacloban. ' data-credit="NOEL CELIS/AFP/Getty Images" data-image="http://www.washingtonpost.com/rw/2010-2019/WashingtonPost/2013/12/06/Outlook/Images/Del6272034.jpg?env=A" data-max-width="3000" data-ratio="1.503" data-title=" " data-uuid="4c4d12da-5ebd-11e3-be07-006c776266ed"></div><div class="wp-volt-gal-slide wp-volt-gal-photo" data-buy="false" data-caption='MYTH: Young adults don’t need health insurance. “Young adults without insurance report difficulties accessing care and paying their medical bills,” Sarah Kliff writes in “&lt;a href="http://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/five-myths-about-young-invincibles/2013/11/26/7caa1dea-5208-11e3-9fe0-fd2ca728e67c_story.html"&gt;Five myths about ‘young invincibles.’&lt;/a&gt;” “A &lt;a data-xslt="_http" href="http://www.commonwealthfund.org/Surveys/2012/Jun/Health-Insurance-Tracking-Survey-of-Young-Adults.aspx"&gt;2011 study&lt;/a&gt; from the Commonwealth Fund found that . . . 51 percent of uninsured young adults had difficulty paying medical bills, with 26 percent having been contacted by a collection ag